title: LEGCO QUESTION NO.4 (Oral Reply)
question_text: Asked by: Dr Hon TANG Siu-tong Date of meeting : 19 May 1999 Replied by : Secretary for Health and Welfare Question: At present, persons seeking treatment at the accident and emergency ("A&E") departments of public hospitals are classified into five categories according to the urgency of their cases, so as to determine their priorities for consultation. In this connection, will the Government inform this Council of :- (a) the respective numbers of persons in

Government inform this Council of :- (a) the respective numbers of persons in
the different categories seeking treatment in different time slots of the day at the
A&E department of each public hospital over the past 3 years, and the percentage of
each category against the total number of persons at that department; (b) the percentage of the operating cost
(please state the items included) for the A&E department of each hospital against the
overall operating cost for that hospital last year; and (c) how the average operating cost for

overall operating cost for that hospital last year; and (c) how the average operating cost for
the A&E department of a public hospital compares to that for a clinic under the
Department of Health in providing night-time out-patient services; whether it has plans to
extend the night-time out-patient services currently provided by the Department of Health,
so as to reduce the workload of the A&E departments of public hospitals?  <u></u>
reply_text:
Madam President, (a) The number of A&E attendances for
each hospital with breakdown by triage categories and the percentage of each category
against the total number of A&E attendances for 1997-98 and 1998-99 are shown in
Tables 1 and 2 respectively. Since it was until 1997-98 that the Hospital Authority (HA)
had clearly defined the various triage categories, HA can only provide the data for the
past two years. In order to understand

past two years. In order to understand
the patients’ usage pattern of A&E services at different hours, in March 1998, HA
conducted a survey at each A&E department to capture the total A&E attendances by
triage categories by hour of the day. According to the information obtained, the A&E
departments recorded the lowest attendance at 2am to 7am, and the highest attendance at

departments recorded the lowest attendance at 2am to 7am, and the highest attendance at
9am to noon, 1pm to 4pm and 8pm to 11pm. The survey results are shown in Table 3. (b) The percentage of the
operating cost for the A&E departments of the major acute hospitals against the
overall hospital operating cost is shown in Table 4. The major elements of the operating
cost include staff salary, drugs and other expenses, such as water and electricity etc.

cost include staff salary, drugs and other expenses, such as water and electricity etc.
Given that the size and service mix of each hospital are different, and the number of
A&E attendances and their case mix are also different, the percentage of operating
cost of A&E departments at different hospitals varies. (c) According to the
information from HA and the Department of Health (DH), in 1998-99, the average A&E
unit cost per attendance is $621, whereas the unit cost for DH’s general outpatient

unit cost per attendance is $621, whereas the unit cost for DH’s general outpatient
clinic service is $218. Since the A&E departments are fully equipped with manpower and
facilities to provide urgent treatment for patients injured in accidents or with acute
diseases, the average operating cost is much higher than that of the general outpatient
clinics which provide treatment for patients with non-acute or less severe diseases. DH
now operates 22 evening clinics, with an average utilization rate of 86%, which have
remaining capacity to meet the needs of more patients. DH will continue to publicize its

remaining capacity to meet the needs of more patients. DH will continue to publicize its
evening clinic services through various channels. We will closely monitor the utilization
rate of the evening clinic service and will review such service when necessary. The
present triage system implemented in the A&E departments of public hospitals can
effectively enable the provision of immediate treatment for critical patients. Also,
almost all of the patients categorized as emergency and urgent cases can receive treatment
within 15 and 30 minutes.   <u></u> Table 1 - The number of
